+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QN> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QP> .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QP> .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QP> .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QP> .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QP> .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QV> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QP> .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QX> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QP> .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/A1> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Hadean is an informal name for the first of the three major intervals of Precambrian time. It is succeeded by the Archean Eon (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Paleoarchean Era is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the second of the four eras of the Archean Eon. It is preceded by the Eoarchean Era and succeeded by the Mesoarchean Era (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AB> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Ectasian Period is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the second of the three periods of the Mesoproterozoic Era. It is preceded by the Calymmian Period and succeeded by the Stenian Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cryogenian Period is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the second of the three periods of the Neoproterozoic Era. It is preceded by the Tonian Period and succeeded by the Ediacaran Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AD> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Ediacaran Period is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the last of the three periods of the Neoproterozoic Era. It is preceded by the Cryogenian Period and succeeded by the Cambrian Period (Paleozoic Era) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/). Replaces: Neoproterozoic Period III."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Eoarchean Era is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the first of the four eras of the Archean Eon. It is preceded by the Hadean and succeeded by the Paleoarchean Era (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AH> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Rhyacian Period is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the second of the four periods of the Paleoproterozoic Era. It is preceded by the Siderian Period and succeeded by the Orosirian Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AI> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Stenian Period is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the last of the three periods of the Mesoproterozoic Era. It is preceded by the Ectasian Period and succeeded by the Tonian Period (Neoproterozoic Era) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Paleoproterozoic Era is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the first of the three eras of the Proterozoic Eon. It is preceded by the Neoarchean Era (Archean Eon) and succeeded by the Mesoproterozoic Era (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mesoarchean Era is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the third of the four eras of the Archean Eon. It is preceded by the Paleoarchean Era and succeeded by the Neoarchean Era (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AN> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Neoarchean Era is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the last of the four eras of the Archean Eon. It is preceded by the Mesoarchean Era and succeeded by the Paleoproterozoic Era (Proterozoic Eon) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Orosirian Period is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the third of the four periods of the Paleoproterozoic Era. It is preceded by the Rhyacian Period and succeeded by the Statherian Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AP> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Proterozoic Eon is the last of the three major intervals of Precambrian time. It is preceded by the Archean Eon, and succeeded by the Phanerozoic Eon (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AQ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Statherian Period is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the last of the four periods of the Paleoproterozoic Era. It is preceded by the Orosirian Period and succeeded by the Calymmian Period (Mesoproterozoic Era) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Archean Eon is the second of the three major intervals of Precambrian time. It is preceded by the Hadean, and succeeded by the Proterozoic Eon (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Siderian Period is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the first of the four periods of the Paleoproterozoic Era. It is preceded by the Archean Eon and succeeded by the Rhyacian Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Tonian Period is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the first of the three periods of the Neoproterozoic Era. It is preceded by the Stenian Period (Mesoproterozoic Era) and succeeded by the Cryogenian Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AX> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mesoproterozoic Era is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the second of the three eras of the Proterozoic Eon. It is preceded by the Paleoproterozoic Era and succeeded by the Neoproterozoic Era (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AY> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Calymmian Period is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the first of the three periods of the Mesoproterozoic Era. It is preceded by the Stratherian Period (Paleoproterozoic Era) and succeeded by the Ectasian Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/AZ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Neoproterozoic Era is a division of Precambrian geological time. It is the last of the three eras of the Proterozoic Eon. It is preceded by the Mesoproterozoic Era and succeeded by the Paleozoic Era (Phanerozoic Eon) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BB> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Bavelian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the Menapian Stage and succeeded by the Cromerian Complex. It is contemporaneous with the latest part of the Beestonian Stage in Great Britain (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cromerian Complex is an Early-to-Mid Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval. It is preceded by the Bavelian Stage and succeeded by the Elsterian Stage. It is contemporanerous with the Cromerian Stage in Great Britain, and with marine isotope stages 13-21 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BD> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Weichselian Stage is the last Late Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval. It is preceded by the Eemian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Devensian Stage in Great Britain (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Eburonian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval. It is preceded by the Tiglian Stage and succeeded by the Waalian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the early part of the Beestonian Stage in Great Britain (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BH> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Holsteinian Stage is a Mid Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval. It is preceded by the Elsterian Stage and succeeded by the Saalian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Hoxnian Stage in Great Britain, and with Marine Isotope Stage 11 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BI> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Eemian Stage is a Late Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval. It is preceded by the Saalian Stage and succeeded by the Weichselian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Ipswichian Stage in Great Britain, and with Marine Isotope Stage 5e (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Elsterian Stage is a Mid Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval. It is preceded by the Cromerian Complex and succeeded by the Holsteinian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Anglian Stage in Great Britain, and with Marine Isotope Stage 12 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Menapian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval. It is preceded by the Waalian Stage and succeeded by the Bavelian Stage. It is contemporaneous with part of the Beestonian Stage in Great Britain (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BP> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Praetiglian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the Reuverian Stage and succeeded by the Tiglian Stage. It is contemporaneous with marine isotope stages 96-100 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Reuverian Stage is a Pliocene-Early Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate interval. It is succeeded by the Praetiglian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BRC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Reuverian Substage C is an Early Pleistocene substage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is succeeded by the Praetiglian Stage (BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Saalian Stage is a Mid Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval. It is preceded by the Holsteinian Stage and succeeded by the Eemian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Wolstonian Stage in Great Britain, and with marine isotope stages 6-10 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Tiglian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the Praetiglian Stage and succeeded by the Eburonian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Ludhamian to Pastonian stages in Great Britain (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BTA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Tiglian Substage A is an Early Pleistocene substage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is the first of three substages within the Tiglian Stage. It is succeeded by Tiglian Substage B. It is contemporaneous with the Ludhamian Stage in Great Britain (BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BTB> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Tiglian Substage B is an Early Pleistocene substage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is the second of three substages within the Tiglian Stage. It is preceded by Tiglian Substage A, and succeeded by Tiglian Substage C. It is contemporaneous with the Thurnian Stage in Great Britain (BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BTC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Tiglian Substage C is an Early Pleistocene substage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is the last of three substages within the Tiglian Stage. It is preceded by Tiglian Substage B. It is contemporaneous with the Antian/Bramertonian-to-Pastonian stages in Great Britain (BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/BW> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Waalian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the NW European Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval. It is preceded by the Eburonian Stage and succeeded by the Menapian Stage. It is contemporaneous with part of the Beestonian Stage in Great Britain (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/C> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Carboniferous Period is the fifth of the six periods of the Paleozoic Era. It is preceded by the Devonian Period and succeeded by the Permian Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Langsettian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of four substages of the Westphalian Stage. It is preceded by the Yeadonian Substage (Namurian Stage) and succeeded by the Duckmantian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5). Replaces: Westphalian Substage A."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CAA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Westphalian Substage A is a deprecated W European Carboniferous term, replaced by Langsettian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CAS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Asturian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the last of four substages of the Westphalian Stage. It is preceded by the Bolsovian Substage and succeeded by the Cantabrian Substage (Stephanian Stage) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5). Replaces: Westphalian Substage D."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CB> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Duckmantian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of four substages of the Westphalian Stage. It is preceded by the Langsettian Substage and succeeded by the Bolsovian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5). Replaces: Westphalian Substage B."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CBB> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Westphalian Substage B is a deprecated W European Carboniferous term, replaced by Duckmantian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CBS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Bashkirian Age is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the only age within the Early Pennsylvanian Epoch. It is preceded by the Serpukhovian Age (Late Mississippian Epoch) and succeeded by the Moscovian Age (Mid Pennsylvanian Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Bolsovian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the third of four substages of the Westphalian Stage. It is preceded by the Duckmantian Substage and succeeded by the Asturian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5). Replaces: Westphalian Substage C."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CCC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Westphalian Substage C is a deprecated W European Carboniferous term, replaced by Bolsovian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CD> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Westphalian Substage D is a deprecated W European Carboniferous term, replaced by Asturian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Pendleian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of seven substages of the Namurian Stage. It is preceded by the Brigantian Substage (Visean Stage) and succeeded by the Arnsbergian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CF> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Courceyan Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the only substage of the Tournaisian Stage. It is succeeded by the Chadian Substage (Visean Stage) (BGS Research Report RR/10/07, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CG> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Arnsbergian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of seven substages of the Namurian Stage. It is preceded by the Pendleian Substage and succeeded by the Chokierian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CGZ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Gzhelian Age is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the second of the two ages within the Late Pennsylvanian Epoch. It is preceded by the Kasimovian Age and succeeded by the Asselian Age (Permian Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CH> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Chokierian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the third of seven substages of the Namurian Stage. It is preceded by the Arnsbergian Substage and succeeded by the Alportian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CI> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Chadian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of five substages of the Visean Stage. It is preceded by the Courceyan Substage (Tournaisian Stage) and succeeded by the Arundian Substage (BGS Research Report RR/10/07, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CJ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Arundian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of five substages of the Visean Stage. It is preceded by the Chadian Substage and succeeded by the Holkerian Substage (BGS Research Report RR/10/07, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CK> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Kinderscoutian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the fifth of seven substages of the Namurian Stage. It is preceded by the Alportian Substage and succeeded by the Marsdenian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CKS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Kasimovian Age is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the first of the two ages within the Late Pennsylvanian Epoch. It is preceded by the Moscovian Age (Mid Pennsylvanian Epoch) and succeeded by the Gzhelian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Dinantian Subsystem is a deprecated European term for the Lower Carboniferous, approximately equating to the Early Mississippian Epoch - Mid Mississippian Epoch interval (Geologic Time Scale 2020, chapter 23; BGS Research Report RR/10/007, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CMI> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mississippian Subperiod is the first of two major subdivisions of the Carboniferous Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CMIE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Mississippian Epoch is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the first of the three epochs within the Mississippian Subperiod. It is preceded by the Late Devonian Epoch (Devonian Period) and succeeded by the Mid Mississippian Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CMIL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Mississippian Epoch is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the last of the three epochs within the Mississippian Subperiod. It is preceded by the Mid Mississippian Epoch and succeeded by the Early Pennsylvanian Epoch (Pennsylvanian Subperiod) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CMIM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mid Mississippian Epoch is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the second of the three epochs within the Mississippian Subperiod. It is preceded by the Early Mississippian Epoch and succeeded by the Late Mississippian Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CMO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Moscovian Age is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the only age within the Mid Pennsylvanian Epoch. It is preceded by the Bashkirian Age (Early Pennsylvanian Epoch) and succeeded by the Kasimovian Age (Late Pennsylvanian Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CN> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Namurian Stage is the third of six stages of the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the Visean Stage and succeeded by the Westphalian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Alportian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the fourth of seven substages of the Namurian Stage. It is preceded by the Chokierian Substage and succeeded by the Kinderscoutian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CPE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Pennsylvanian Subperiod is the second of two major subdivisions of the Carboniferous Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CPEE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Pennsylvanian Epoch is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the first of the three epochs within the Pennsylvanian Subperiod. It is preceded by the Late Mississippian Epoch (Mississippian Subperiod) and succeeded by the Mid Pennsylvanian Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CPEL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Pennsylvanian Epoch is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the last of the three epochs within the Pennsylvanian Subperiod. It is preceded by the Mid Pennsylvanian Epoch and succeeded by the Cisuralian Epoch (Permian Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CPEM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mid Pennsylvanian Epoch is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the second of the three epochs within the Pennsylvanian Subperiod. It is preceded by the Early Pennsylvanian Epoch and succeeded by the Late Pennsylvanian Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CQ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Holkerian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the third of five substages of the Visean Stage. It is preceded by the Arundian Substage and succeeded by the Asbian Substage (BGS Research Report RR/10/07, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Asbian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the fourth of five substages of the Visean Stage. It is preceded by the Holkerian Substage and succeeded by the Brigantian Substage (BGS Research Report RR/10/07, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Stephanian Stage is the fifth of six stages of the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the Westphalian Stage and succeeded by the Autunian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CSA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Stephanian Substage A is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of four substages of the Stephanian Stage. It is preceded by the Cantabrian Substage and succeeded by Stephanian Substage B (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CSB> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Stephanian Substage B is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the third of four substages of the Stephanian Stage. It is preceded by Stephanian Substage A and succeeded by Stephanian Substage C (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CSC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Stephanian Substage C is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the last of four substages of the Stephanian Stage. It is preceded by Stephanian Substage B and succeeded by the Autunian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CSR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Serpukhovian Age is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the only age within the Late Mississippian Epoch. It is preceded by the Visean Age (Mid Mississippian Epoch) and succeeded by the Bashkirian Age (Early Pennsylvanian Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CST> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cantabrian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of four substages of the Stephanian Stage. It is preceded by the Asturian Substage (Westphalian Stage) and succeeded by Stephanian Substage A (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Tournaisian Age is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the only age within the Early Mississippian Epoch. It is preceded by the Famennian Age (Devonian Period) and succeeded by the Visean Age (Mid Mississippian Epoch). The Tournaisian is also the first of six stages comprising the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme, succeeded by the Visean Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.5; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CU> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Silesian Subsystem is a deprecated European term for the Upper Carboniferous, approximately equating to the Late Mississippian Epoch - Late Pennsylvanian Epoch interval (Geologic Time Scale 2020, chapter 23; BGS Research Report RR/10/007, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CUT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Autunian Stage is the last of six stages of the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme, and extends into the Permian Period. It is preceded by the Stephanian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5, 24.9)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CV> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Visean Age is a division of geological time within the Carboniferous Period. It is the only age within the Mid Mississippian Epoch. It is preceded by the Tournaisian Age (Early Mississippian Epoch) and succeeded by the Serpukhovian Age (Late Mississippian Epoch). The Visean is also the second of six stages comprising the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme, preceded by the Tournaisian Stage and succeeded by the Namurian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 23.5; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CW> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Westphalian Stage is the fourth of six stages of the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the Namurian Stage and succeeded by the Stephanian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CX> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Brigantian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the last of five substages of the Visean Stage. It is preceded by the Asbian Substage and succeeded by the Pendleian Substage (Namurian Stage) (BGS Research Report RR/10/07, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CY> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Yeadonian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the last of seven substages of the Namurian Stage. It is preceded by the Marsdenian Substage and succeeded by the Langsettian Substage (Westphalian Stage) (Geologic Time scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/CZ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marsdenian Substage is a substage in the British regional Carboniferous stratigraphic scheme. It is the sixth of seven substages of the Namurian Stage. It is preceded by the Kinderscoutian Substage and succeeded by the Yeadonian Substage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 23.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/D> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Devonian Period is the fourth of the six periods of the Paleozoic Era. It is preceded by the Silurian Period and succeeded by the Carboniferous Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 22.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/DA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Famennian Age is a division of geological time within the Devonian Period. It is the second of the two ages within the Late Devonian Epoch. It is preceded by the Frasnian Age and succeeded by the Early Mississippian Epoch (Carboniferous Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 22.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/DE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Emsian Age is a division of geological time within the Devonian Period. It is the last of the three ages within the Early Devonian Epoch. It is preceded by the Pragian Age and succeeded by the Eifelian Age (Mid Devonian Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 22.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/DI> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Eifelian Age is a division of geological time within the Devonian Period. It is the first of the two ages within the Mid Devonian Epoch. It is preceded by the Emsian Age (Early Devonian Epoch) and succeeded by the Givetian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 22.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/DL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Devonian Epoch is the first of the three epochs of the Devonian Period. It is preceded by the Pridoli Epoch (Silurian Period) and succeeded by the Mid Devonian Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 22.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/DM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mid Devonian Epoch is the second of the three epochs of the Devonian Period. It is preceded by the Early Devonian Epoch and succeeded by the Late Devonian Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 22.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/DO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Lochkovian Age is a division of geological time within the Devonian Period. It is the first of the three ages within the Early Devonian Epoch. It is preceded by the Pridoli Epoch (Silurian Period) and succeeded by the Pragian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 22.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/DP> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Pragian Age is a division of geological time within the Devonian Period. It is the second of the three ages within the Early Devonian Epoch. It is preceded by the Lochkovian Age and succeeded by the Emsian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 22.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/DR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Frasnian Age is a division of geological time within the Devonian Period. It is the first of the two ages within the Late Devonian Epoch. It is preceded by the Givetian Age (Mid Devonian Epoch) and succeeded by the Famennian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 22.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/DU> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Devonian Epoch is the last of the three epochs of the Devonian Period. It is preceded by the Mid Devonian Epoch and succeeded by the Early Mississippian Epoch (Carboniferous Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 22.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/DV> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Givetian Age is a division of geological time within the Devonian Period. It is the second of the two ages within the Mid Devonian Epoch. It is preceded by the Eifelian Age and succeeded by the Frasnian Age (Late Devonian Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 22.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/E> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cambrian Period is the first of the six periods of the Palaeozoic Era. It is preceded by the Ediacaran Period (Neoproterozoic Era) and succeeded by the Ordovician Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/E02> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cambrian Stage 2 is a division of geological time within the Cambrian Period. It is the second of the two ages of the Terreneuvian Epoch. It is preceded by the Fortunian Age and succeeded by Cambrian Stage 3 (of Cambrian Series 2) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/E03> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cambrian Stage 3 is a division of geological time within the Cambrian Period. It is the first of the two ages within Cambrian Series 2. It is preceded by Cambrian Stage 2 (Terreneuvian Epoch) and succeeded by Cambrian Stage 4 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/E04> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cambrian Stage 4 is a division of geological time within the Cambrian Period. It is the second of the two ages within Cambrian Series 2. It is preceded by Cambrian Stage 3 and succeeded by the Wuliuan Age (of the Miaolingian Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/E05> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Wuliuan Age is a division of geological time within the Cambrian Period. It is the first of the three ages within the Miaolingian Epoch. It is preceded by Cambrian Stage 4 (of Cambrian Series 2) and succeeded by the Drumian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/E08> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Paibian Age is a division of geological time within the Cambrian Period. It is the first of the three ages within the Furongian Epoch. It is preceded by the Guzhangian Age (of the Miaolingian Epoch) and succeeded by the Jiangshanian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/E09> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Jiangshanian Age is a division of geological time within the Cambrian Period. It is the second of the three ages within the Furongian Epoch. It is preceded by the Paibian Age and succeeded by Cambrian Stage 10 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/E10> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cambrian Stage 10 is a division of geological time within the Cambrian Period. It is the last of the three ages within the Furongian Epoch. It is preceded by the Jiangshanian Age and succeeded by the Tremadocian Age (Ordovician Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/E2> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cambrian Series 2 is the second of the four epochs of the Cambrian Period. It is preceded by the Terreneuvian Epoch and succeeded by the Miaolingian Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/E3> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Miaolingian Epoch is the third of the four epochs of the Cambrian Period. It is preceded by Cambrian Series 2 and succeeded by the Furongian Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/EC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Comley Series is the first of three series in the British regional Cambrian stratigraphic scheme. It is succeeded by the St David's Series."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/ED> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "St David's Series is the second of three series in the British regional Cambrian stratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the Comley Series and succeeded by the Merioneth Series."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/EDM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Drumian Age is a division of geological time within the Cambrian Period. It is the second of the three ages within the Miaolingian Epoch. It is preceded by the Wuliuan Age and succeeded by the Guzhangian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/EF> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Furongian Epoch is the last of the four epochs of the Cambrian Period. It is preceded by the Miaolingian Epoch and succeeded by the Early Ordovician Epoch (Ordovician Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/EFT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Fortunian Age is a division of geological time within the Cambrian Period. It is the first of the two ages of the Terreneuvian Epoch. It is preceded by the Ediacaran Period (Precambrian) and succeeded by Cambrian Stage 2 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/EGZ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Guzhangian Age is a division of geological time within the Cambrian Period. It is the last of the three ages within the Miaolingian Epoch. It is preceded by the Drumian Age and succeeded by the Paibian Age (Furongian Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/EM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Merioneth Series is the last of three series in the British regional Cambrian stratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the St David's Series."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/EN> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Terreneuvian Epoch is the first of the four epochs of the Cambrian Period. It is preceded by the Ediacaran Period and succeeded by Cambrian Series 2 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 19.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/FH> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Phanerozoic Eon is the time interval characterised by deposition of rocks containing abundant evidence of life. It is the eon in which we live. It is preceded by the Proterozoic Eon (Precambrian) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/G> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Paleogene Period is the first of the three periods of the Cenozoic Era. It is preceded by the Cretaceous Period (Mesozoic Era) and succeeded by the Neogene Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GB> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Bartonian Age is a division of geological time within the Paleogene Period. It is the third of the four ages within the Eocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Lutetian Age and succeeded by the Priabonian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Chattian Age is a division of geological time within the Paleogene Period. It is the second of the two ages within the Oligocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Rupelian Age and succeeded by the Aquitanian Age (Neogene Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GD> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Danian Age is a division of geological time within the Paleogene Period. It is the first of the three ages within the Paleocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Maastrichtian Age (Cretaceous Period) and succeeded by the Selandian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Eocene Epoch is the second of the three epochs of the Paleogene Period. It is preceded by the Paleocene Epoch and succeeded by the Oligocene Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GEE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Eocene is the first of three informal subdivisions of the Eocene Epoch. It equates to the Ypresian Age of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GEL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Eocene is the last of three informal subdivisions of the Eocene Epoch. It equates to the Priabonian Age of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GEM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mid Eocene is the second of three informal subdivisions of the Eocene Epoch. It equates to the Lutetian plus Bartonian ages of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GI> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Priabonian Age is a division of geological time within the Paleogene Period. It is the last of the four ages within the Eocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Bartonian Age and succeeded by the Rupelian Age (Oligocene Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Lutetian Age is a division of geological time within the Paleogene Period. It is the second of the four ages within the Eocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Ypresian Age and succeeded by the Bartonian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Oligocene Epoch is the last of the three epochs of the Paleogene Period. It is preceded by the Eocene Epoch and succeeded by the Miocene Epoch (Neogene Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GOE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Oligocene is the first of two informal subdivisions of the Oligocene Epoch. It equates to the Rupelian Age of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GOL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Oligocene is the second of two informal subdivisions of the Oligocene Epoch. It equates to the Chattian Age of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GP> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Paleocene Epoch is the first of the three epochs of the Paleogene Period. It is preceded by the Late Cretaceous Epoch (Cretaceous Period) and succeeded by the Eocene Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GPE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Paleocene is the first of three informal subdivisions of the Paleocene Epoch. It equates to the Danian Age of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GPL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Paleocene is the last of three informal subdivisions of the Paleocene Epoch. It equates to the Thanetian Age of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GPM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mid Paleocene is the second of three informal subdivisions of the Paleocene Epoch. It equates to the Selandian Age of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Rupelian Age is a division of geological time within the Paleogene Period. It is the first of the two ages within the Oligocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Priabonian Age (Eocene Epoch) and succeeded by the Chattian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Selandian Age is a division of geological time within the Paleogene Period. It is the second of the three ages within the Paleocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Danian Age and succeeded by the Thanetian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Thanetian Age is a division of geological time within the Paleogene Period. It is the last of the three ages within the Paleocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Selandian Age and succeeded by the Ypresian Age (Eocene Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/GY> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Ypresian Age is a division of geological time within the Paleogene Period. It is the first of the four ages within the Eocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Thanetian Age (Paleocene Epoch) and succeeded by the Lutetian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 28.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/IZ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cenozoic Era is the last of the three eras of the Phanerozoic Eon. It includes the Paleogene, Neogene and Quaternary periods. It is the era in which we live. It is preceded by the Mesozoic Era (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/IZT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Tertiary is a deprecated term, traditionally used for the interval between the Mesozoic and the Quaternary. It is replaced in modern usage by the Paleogene and Neogene periods (Geologic Time Scale 2012, chapter 28)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/J> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Jurassic Period is the second of the three periods of the Mesozoic Era. It is preceded by the Triassic Period and succeeded by the Cretaceous Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Aalenian Age is a division of geological time within the Jurassic Period. It is the first of the four ages within the Mid Jurassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Toarcian Age (Early Jurassic Epoch) and succeeded by the Bajocian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JB> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Bajocian Age is a division of geological time within the Jurassic Period. It is the second of the four ages within the Mid Jurassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Aalenian Age and succeeded by the Bathonian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Callovian Age is a division of geological time within the Jurassic Period. It is the last of the four ages within the Mid Jurassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Bathonian Age and succeeded by the Oxfordian Age (Late Jurassic Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JD> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Kimmeridgian Age is a division of geological time within the Jurassic Period. It is the second of the three ages within the Late Jurassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Oxfordian Age and succeeded by the Tithonian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Pliensbachian Age is a division of geological time within the Jurassic Period. It is the third of the four ages within the Early Jurassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Sinemurian Age and succeeded by the Toarcian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JH> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Hettangian Age is a division of geological time within the Jurassic Period. It is the first of the four ages within the Early Jurassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Rhaetian Age (Triassic Period) and succeeded by the Sinemurian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JI> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Tithonian Age is a division of geological time within the Jurassic Period. It is the last of the three ages within the Late Jurassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Kimmeridgian Age and succeeded by the Berriasian Age (Cretaceous Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Jurassic Epoch is the first of the three epochs of the Jurassic Period. It is preceded by the Late Triassic Epoch (Triassic Period) and succeeded by the Mid Jurassic Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mid Jurassic Epoch is the second of the three epochs of the Jurassic Period. It is preceded by the Early Jurassic Epoch and succeeded by the Late Jurassic Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JN> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Bathonian Age is a division of geological time within the Jurassic Period. It is the third of the four ages within the Mid Jurassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Bajocian Age and succeeded by the Callovian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Oxfordian Age is a division of geological time within the Jurassic Period. It is the first of the three ages within the Late Jurassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Callovian Age (Mid Jurassic Epoch) and succeeded by the Kimmeridgian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JP> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Portlandian Stage is a deprecated term, a British regional stage approximately equating to the late Tithonian Age (Jurassic Period) - earliest Berriasian Age (Cretaceous Period) interval (Geologic Time Scale 2012, fig. 26.8)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Sinemurian Age is a division of geological time within the Jurassic Period. It is the second of the four ages within the Early Jurassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Hettangian Age and succeeded by the Pliensbachian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Toarcian Age is a division of geological time within the Jurassic Period. It is the last of the four ages within the Early Jurassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Pliensbachian Age and succeeded by the Aalenian Age (Mid Jurassic Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JU> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Jurassic Epoch is the last of the three epochs of the Jurassic Period. It is preceded by the Mid Jurassic Epoch and succeeded by the Early Cretaceous Epoch (Cretaceous Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 26.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/JV> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Volgian Stage is a deprecated term, a European regional stage approximately equating to the Tithonian Age (Jurassic Period) - earliest Berriasian Age (Cretaceous Period) interval (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 26.9)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/K> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cretaceous Period is the third of the three periods of the Mesozoic Era. It is preceded by the Jurassic Period and succeeded by the Paleogene Period (Cenozoic Era) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Albian Age is a division of geological time within the Cretaceous Period. It is the last of the six ages within the Early Cretaceous Epoch. It is preceded by the Aptian Age and succeeded by the Cenomanian Age (Late Cretaceous Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KB> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Barremian Age is a division of geological time within the Cretaceous Period. It is the fourth of the six ages within the Early Cretaceous Epoch. It is preceded by the Hauterivian Age and succeeded by the Aptian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Campanian Age is a division of geological time within the Cretaceous Period. It is the fifth of the six ages within the Late Cretaceous Epoch. It is preceded by the Santonian Age and succeeded by the Maastrichtian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cenomanian Age is a division of geological time within the Cretaceous Period. It is the first of the six ages within the Late Cretaceous Epoch. It is preceded by the Albian Age (Early Cretaceous Epoch) and succeeded by the Turonian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KH> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Hauterivian Age is a division of geological time within the Cretaceous Period. It is the third of the six ages within the Early Cretaceous Epoch. It is preceded by the Valanginian Age and succeeded by the Barremian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Cretaceous Epoch is the first of the two epochs of the Cretaceous Period. It is preceded by the Late Jurassic Epoch (Jurassic Period) and succeeded by the Late Cretaceous Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Maastrichtian Age is a division of geological time within the Cretaceous Period. It is the last of the six ages within the Late Cretaceous Epoch. It is preceded by the Campanian Age and succeeded by the Danian Age (Paleogene Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Coniacian Age is a division of geological time within the Cretaceous Period. It is the third of the six ages within the Late Cretaceous Epoch. It is preceded by the Turonian Age and succeeded by the Santonian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KP> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Aptian Age is a division of geological time within the Cretaceous Period. It is the fifth of the six ages within the Early Cretaceous Epoch. It is preceded by the Barremian Age and succeeded by the Albian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Berriasian Age is a division of geological time within the Cretaceous Period. It is the first of the six ages within the Early Cretaceous Epoch. It is preceded by the Tithonian Age (Jurassic Period) and succeeded by the Valanginian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Santonian Age is a division of geological time within the Cretaceous Period. It is the fourth of the six ages within the Late Cretaceous Epoch. It is preceded by the Coniacian Age and succeeded by the Campanian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Turonian Age is a division of geological time within the Cretaceous Period. It is the second of the six ages within the Late Cretaceous Epoch. It is preceded by the Cenomanian Age and succeeded by the Coniacian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KU> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Cretaceous Epoch is the second of the two epochs of the Cretaceous Period. It is preceded by the Early Cretaceous Epoch and succeeded by the Paleocene Epoch (Paleogene Period) Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KV> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Valanginian Age is a division of geological time within the Cretaceous Period. It is the second of the six ages within the Early Cretaceous Epoch. It is preceded by the Berriasian Age and succeeded by the Hauterivian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 27.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/KZ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Ryazanian Stage is a deprecated term, a British Cretaceous regional stage approximately equating to the Berriasian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 26.9)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/MZ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mesozoic Era is the second of the three eras of the Phanerozoic Eon. It includes the Triassic, Jurassic and Cretaceous periods. It is preceded by the Paleozoic Era and succeeded by the Cenozoic Era (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/N> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Neogene Period is the second of the three periods of the Cenozoic Era. It is preceded by the Paleogene Period and succeeded by the Quaternary Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 29.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/N1> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Prior to the 2009 decision by the International Union of Geological Sciences (IUGS) to place the base of the Quaternary Period at a level coinciding with the base of the Gelasian Age, the Neogene Period was considered to include the Gelasian Age and to have an upper boundary at approximately 1.8 Ma BP. This is now a deprecated definition and equates to the modern Neogene Period - Gelasian Age interval (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Aquitanian Age is a division of geological time within the Neogene Period. It is the first of the six ages within the Miocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Chattian Age (Paleogene Period) and succeeded by the Burdigalian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 29.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NB> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Burdigalian Age is a division of geological time within the Neogene Period. It is the second of the six ages within the Miocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Aquitanian Age and succeeded by the Langhian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 29.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Piacenzian Age is a division of geological time within the Neogene Period. It is the second of the two ages within the Pliocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Zanclean Age and succeeded by the Gelasian Age (Quaternary Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 29.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/). Replaces: Waltonian Age."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Messinian Age is a division of geological time within the Neogene Period. It is the last of the six ages within the Miocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Tortonian Age and succeeded by the Zanclean Age (Pliocene Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 29.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NI> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Prior to the 2009 decision by the International Union of Geological Sciences (IUGS) to place the base of the Quaternary Period at a level coinciding with the base of the Gelasian Age, the Piacenzian Age was considered to have an upper boundary at approximately 1.8 Ma BP. This is now a deprecated definition and equates to the modern Piacenzian Age - Gelasian Age interval (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Langhian Age is a division of geological time within the Neogene Period. It is the third of the six ages within the Miocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Burdigalian Age and succeeded by the Serravallian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 29.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Miocene Epoch is the first of the two epochs of the Neogene Period. It is preceded by the Oligocene Epoch (Paleogene Period) and succeeded by the Pliocene Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 29.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NME> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Miocene is the first of three informal subdivisions of the Miocene Epoch. It equates to the Aquitanian plus Burdigalian ages of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NML> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Miocene is the last of three informal subdivisions of the Miocene Epoch. It equates to the Tortonian plus Messinian ages of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NMM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mid Miocene is the second of three informal subdivisions of the Miocene Epoch. It equates to the Langhian plus Serravallian ages of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Prior to the 2009 decision by the International Union of Geological Sciences (IUGS) to place the base of the Quaternary Period at a level coinciding with the base of the Gelasian Age, the Pliocene Epoch was considered to include the Gelasian Age and to have an upper boundary at approximately 1.8 Ma BP. This is now a deprecated definition and equates to the modern Pliocene Epoch - Gelasian Age interval (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NOE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Pliocene is the first of two informal subdivisions of the Pliocene Epoch. It equates to the Zanclean Age of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NOL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Pliocene is the second of two informal subdivisions of the Pliocene Epoch. It equates to the Piacenzian Age of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NP> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Pliocene Epoch is the second of the two epochs of the Neogene Period. It is preceded by the Miocene Epoch and succeeded by the Pleistocene Epoch (Quaternary Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 29.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Serravallian Age is a division of geological time within the Neogene Period. It is the fourth of the six ages within the Miocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Langhian Age and succeeded by the Tortonian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 29.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Tortonian Age is a division of geological time within the Neogene Period. It is the fifth of the six ages within the Miocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Serravallian Age and succeeded by the Messinian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 29.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NW> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Waltonian Age is a deprecated Neogene term, replaced by Piacenzian Age."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/NZ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Zanclean Age is a division of geological time within the Neogene Period. It is the first of the two ages within the Pliocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Messinian Age (Miocene Epoch) and succeeded by the Piacenzian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 29.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/O> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Ordovician Period is the second of the six periods of the Paleozoic Era. It is preceded by the Cambrian Period and succeeded by the Silurian Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 20.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/O1> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Tremadoc Series is the first of five series in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is succeeded by the Arenig Series (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/O2> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Abereiddian Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of two stages of the Llanvirn Series. It is preceded by the Fennian Stage (Arenig Series) and succeeded by the Llandeilian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/O3> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Llandeilian Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of two stages of the Llanvirn Series. It is preceded by the Abereiddian Stage and succeeded by the Aurelucian Stage (Caradoc Series) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/O4> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Caradoc Series is the fourth of five series in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the Llanvirn Series and succeeded by the Ashgill Series (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Ashgill Series is the last of five series in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the Caradoc Series (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OB> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Moridunian Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of three stages of the Arenig Series. It is preceded by the Migneintian Stage (Tremadoc Series) and succeeded by the Whitlandian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OCR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cressagian Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of two stages of the Tremadoc Series. It is succeeded by the Migneintian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/ODP> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Dapingian Age is a division of geological time within the Ordovician Period. It is the first of the two ages within the Mid Ordovician Epoch. It is preceded by the Floian Age (Early Ordovician Epoch) and succeeded by the Darriwilian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 20.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/ODW> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Darriwilian Age is a division of geological time within the Ordovician Period. It is the second of the two ages within the Mid Ordovician Epoch. It is preceded by the Dapingian Age and succeeded by the Sandbian Age (Late Ordovician Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 20.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Llanvirn Series is the third of five series in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the Arenig Series and succeeded by the Caradoc Series (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OEA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Ordovician Epoch is the first of the three epochs of the Ordovician Period. It is preceded by the Furongian Epoch (Cambrian Period) and succeeded by the Mid Ordovician Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 20.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OF> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Fennian Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the last of three stages of the Arenig Series. It is preceded by the Whitlandian Stage and succeeded by the Abereiddian Stage (Llanvirn Series) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OFL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Floian Age is a division of geological time within the Ordovician Period. It is the second of the two ages within the Early Ordovician Epoch. It is preceded by the Tremadocian Age and succeeded by the Dapingian Age (Mid Ordovician Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 20.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OG> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Harnagian Substage is a substage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of three substages of the Burrellian Stage. It is preceded by the Costonian Substage (Aurelucian Stage) and succeeded by the Soudleyan Substage (BGS Research Report RR/12/04, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OH> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Hirnantian Age is a division of geological time within the Ordovician Period. It is the last of the three ages within the Late Ordovician Epoch. It is preceded by the Katian Age and succeeded by the Rhuddanian Age (Silurian Period). The Hirnantian Stage is also the last of four stages in the Ashgill Series in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the Rawtheyan Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 20.1, 20.12; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OI> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Whitlandian Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of three stages of the Arenig Series. It is preceded by the Moridunian Stage and succeeded by the Fennian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OJ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Aurelucian Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of four stages of the Caradoc Series. It is preceded by the Llandeilian Stage (Llanvirn Series) and succeeded by the Burrellian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OK> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Burrellian Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of four stages of the Caradoc Series. It is preceded by the Aurelucian Stage and succeeded by the Cheneyan Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OKA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Katian Age is a division of geological time within the Ordovician Period. It is the second of the three ages within the Late Ordovician Epoch. It is preceded by the Sandbian Age and succeeded by the Hirnantian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 20.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Longvillian Substage is a substage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the last of three substages of the Burrellian Stage. It is preceded by the Soudleyan Substage and succeeded by the Woolstonian Substage (Cheneyan Stage) (BGS Research Report RR/12/04, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OLA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Ordovician Epoch is the last of the three epochs of the Ordovician Period. It is preceded by the Mid Ordovician Epoch and succeeded by the Llandovery Epoch (Silurian Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 20.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marshbrookian Substage is a substage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of two substages of the Cheneyan Stage. It is preceded by the Woolstonian Substage and succeeded by the Actonian Substage (Streffordian Stage) (BGS Research Report RR/12/04, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OMD> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mid Ordovician Epoch is the second of the three epochs of the Ordovician Period. It is preceded by the Early Ordovician Epoch and succeeded by the Late Ordovician Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 20.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OMG> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Migneintian Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of two stages of the Tremadoc Series. It is preceded by the Cressagian Stage and succeeded by the Moridunian Stage (Arenig Series) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/ON> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Onnian Substage is a substage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of two substages of the Streffordian Stage. It is preceded by the Actonian Substage and succeeded by the Pusgillian Stage (BGS Research Report RR/12/04, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Costonian Substage is a substage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of two substages of the Aurelucian Stage. It is preceded by the Velfreyan Substage and succeeded by the Harnagian Substage (Burrellian Stage) (BGS Research Report RR/12/04, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OP> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Pusgillian Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of four stages of the Ashgill Series. It is preceded by the Streffordian Stage (Caradoc Series) and succeeded by the Cautleyan Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OQ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cheneyan Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the third of four stages of the Caradoc Series. It is preceded by the Burrellian Stage and succeeded by the Streffordian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Arenig Series is the second of five series in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is preceded by the Tremadoc Series and succeeded by the Llanvirn Series (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Woolstonian Substage is a substage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of two substages of the Cheneyan Stage. It is preceded by the Longvillian Substage (Burrellian Stage) and succeeded by the Marshbrookian Substage (BGS Research Report RR/12/04, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OSA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Sandbian Age is a division of geological time within the Ordovician Period. It is the first of the three ages within the Late Ordovician Epoch. It is preceded by the Darriwilian Age (Mid Ordovician Epoch) and succeeded by the Katian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 20.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Actonian Substage is a substage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of two substages of the Streffordian Stage. It is preceded by the Marshbrookian Substage (Cheneyan Stage) and succeeded by the Onnian Substage (BGS Research Report RR/12/04, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OTR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Tremadocian Age is a division of geological time within the Ordovician Period. It is the first of the two ages within the Early Ordovician Epoch. It is preceded by Cambrian Stage 10 (Cambrian Period) and succeeded by the Floian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 20.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OU> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cautleyan Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of four stages of the Ashgill Series. It is preceded by the Pusgillian Stage and succeeded by the Rawtheyan Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OW> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Rawtheyan Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the third of four stages of the Ashgill Series. It is preceded by the Cautleyan Stage and succeeded by the Hirnantian Stage (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OX> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Streffordian Stage is a stage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the last of four stages of the Caradoc Series. It is preceded by the Cheneyan Stage and succeeded by the Pusgillian Stage (Ashgill Series) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 20.12)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OY> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Soudleyan Substage is a substage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the second of three substages of the Burrellian Stage. It is preceded by the Harnagian Substage and succeeded by the Longvillian Substage (BGS Research Report RR/12/04, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/OZ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Velfreyan Substage is a substage in the British regional Ordovician stratigraphic scheme. It is the first of two substages of the Aurelucian Stage. It is preceded by the Llandeilian Stage and succeeded by the Costonian Substage (BGS Research Report RR/12/04, table 1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/P> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Permian Period is the last of the six periods of the Paleozoic Era. It is preceded by the Carboniferous Period and succeeded by the Triassic Period (Mesozoic Era) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Asselian Age is a division of geological time within the Permian Period. It is the first of the four ages within the Cisuralian Epoch. It is preceded by the Gzhelian Age (Carboniferous Period) and succeeded by the Sakmarian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PF> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Ufimian-Kazanian Age is a deprecated term, used for Permian rocks on the Russian Platform, approximately equating to the upper Kungurian Age - Roadian Age interval (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 24.9)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PI> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Artinskian Age is a division of geological time within the Permian Period. It is the third of the four ages within the Cisuralian Epoch. It is preceded by the Sakmarian Age and succeeded by the Kungurian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PK> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Kungurian Age is a division of geological time within the Permian Period. It is the last of the four ages within the Cisuralian Epoch. It is preceded by the Artinskian Age and succeeded by the Roadian Age (Guadalupian Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Permian is a deprecated term, replaced by Cisuralian Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 1.4)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PLC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cisuralian Epoch is the first of the three epochs of the Permian Period. It is preceded by the Late Pennsylvanian Epoch (Carboniferous Period) and succeeded by the Guadalupian Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/). Replaces: Early Permian Epoch."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Sakmarian Age is a division of geological time within the Permian Period. It is the second of the four ages within the Cisuralian Epoch. It is preceded by the Asselian Age and succeeded by the Artinskian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Tatarian Age is a deprecated term, used for Permian rocks on the Russian Platform, approximately equating to the Wordian Age - lower Wuchiapingian Age interval (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 24.9)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PU> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Permian is a deprecated term, equating to the Guadalupian Epoch - Lopingian Epoch interval (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 1.4)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PUC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Capitanian Age is a division of geological time within the Permian Period. It is the last of the three ages within the Guadalupian Epoch. It is preceded by the Wordian Age and succeeded by the Wuchiapingian Age (Lopingian Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PUD> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Wordian Age is a division of geological time within the Permian Period. It is the second of the three ages within the Guadalupian Epoch. It is preceded by the Roadian Age and succeeded by the Capitanian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PUG> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Guadalupian Epoch is the second of the three epochs of the Permian Period. It is preceded by the Cisuralian Epoch and succeeded by the Lopingian Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PUH> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Changhsingian Age is a division of geological time within the Permian Period. It is the second of the two ages within the Lopingian Epoch. It is preceded by the Wuchiapingian Age and succeeded by the Induan Age (Triassic Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PUL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Lopingian Epoch is the last of the three epochs of the Permian Period. It is preceded by the Guadalupian Epoch and succeeded by the Early Triassic Epoch (Triassic Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PUR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Roadian Age is a division of geological time within the Permian Period. It is the first of the three ages within the Guadalupian Epoch. It is preceded by the Kungurian Age (Cisuralian Epoch) and succeeded by the Wordian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/PUW> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Wuchiapingian Age is a division of geological time within the Permian Period. It is the first of the two ages within the Lopingian Epoch. It is preceded by the Capitanian Age (Guadalupian Epoch) and succeeded by the Changhsingian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 24.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/Q> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Quaternary Period is the last of the three periods of the Cenozoic Era. It is the period in which we live. It is preceded by the Neogene Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 30.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/Q1> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Prior to the 2009 decision by the International Union of Geological Sciences (IUGS) to place the base of the Quaternary Period at a level coinciding with the base of the Gelasian Age, the Quaternary Period was considered not to include the Gelasian Age and to have a lower boundary at approximately 1.8 Ma BP. This is now a deprecated definition and equates to the modern Calabrian Age - Holocene Epoch interval (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/Q2> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Prior to the 2009 decision by the International Union of Geological Sciences (IUGS) to place the base of the Quaternary Period at a level coinciding with the base of the Gelasian Age, the Pleistocene Epoch was considered not to include the Gelasian Age and to have a lower boundary at approximately 1.8 Ma BP. This is now a deprecated definition and equates to the modern Calabrian Age - Tarantian Age interval (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.1)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/Q2C> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Calabrian Age is a division of geological time within the Quaternary Period. It is the second of the four ages within the Pleistocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Gelasian Age and succeeded by the Chibanian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 30.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/Q2G> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Gelasian Age is a division of geological time within the Quaternary Period. It is the first of the four ages within the Pleistocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Piacenzian Age (Neogene Period) and succeeded by the Calabrian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 30.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/Q2I> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Chibanian Age is a division of geological time within the Quaternary Period. It is the third of the four ages within the Pleistocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Calabrian Age and succeeded by the Upper Pleistocene Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 30.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/). Replaces: Ionian Age."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/Q2T> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Upper Pleistocene Age (unnamed) is a division of geological time within the Quaternary Period. It is the last of the four ages within the Pleistocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Chibanian Age and succeeded by the Holocene Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 30.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/). Replaces: Tarantian Age."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Anglian Stage is a Mid Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval. It is preceded by the Cromerian Stage and succeeded by the Hoxnian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Elsterian Stage of NW Europe, and with Marine Isotope Stage 12 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QB> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Beestonian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval. It is preceded by the Pastonian Stage and succeeded by the Cromerian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Eburonian to Bavelian stages of NW Europe (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b). It is named for the village of Beeston, Norfolk, England."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Cromerian Stage is an Early-to-Mid Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval. It is preceded by the Beestonian Stage and succeeded by the Anglian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Cromerian Complex of NW Europe, and with marine isotope stages 13-21 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QD> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Devensian Stage is the last Late Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval. It is preceded by the Ipswichian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Weichselian Stage in NW Europe (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QDD> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Dimlington Stadial is a relatively cold period near the end of the Devensian Stage. It is succeeded by the Windermere Interstadial (BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b; BGS British Regional Geology: Northern England (Fifth edition), fig. 64)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QDL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Loch Lomond Stadial is a relatively cold period near the end of the Devensian Stage. It is preceded by the Windermere Interstadial (BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b; BGS British Regional Geology: Northern England (Fifth edition), fig. 64)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QDW> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Windermere Interstadial is a relatively warm period near the end of the Devensian Stage. It is preceded by the Dimlington Stadial and succeeded by the Loch Lomond Stadial (BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b; BGS British Regional Geology: Northern England (Fifth edition), fig. 64)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Baventian Stage is a deprecated term, replaced by Pre-Pastonian/Baventian Stage (BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QF> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Flandrian Age is a deprecated term, replaced by Holocene Epoch (Geologic time Scale 2020, chapter 30)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QH> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Holocene Epoch is the second of the two epochs of the Quaternary Period. It is the epoch in which we live. It is preceded by the Pleistocene Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 30.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/). Replaces: Flandrian Age."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QHE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Greenlandian Age is a division of geological time within the Quaternary Period. It is the first of three ages within the Holocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Upper Pleistocene Age (Pleistocene Epoch) and succeeded by the Northgrippian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 30.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QHL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Meghalayan Age is a division of geological time within the Quaternary Period. It is the last of three ages within the Holocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Northgrippian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 30.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QHM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Northgrippian Age is a division of geological time within the Quaternary Period. It is the second of three ages within the Holocene Epoch. It is preceded by the Greenlandian Age and succeeded by the Meghalayan Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 30.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QI> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Ipswichian Stage is a Late Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval. It is preceded by the Wolstonian Stage and succeeded by the Devensian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Eemian Stage of NW Europe, and with Marine Isotope Stage 5e (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b). It is named for the town of Ipswich, Suffolk, England."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Ludhamian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval. It is preceded by the Pre-Ludhamian Stage and succeeded by the Thurnian Stage. It is contemporaneous with Tiglian Substage A of NW Europe (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b). It is named for the town of Ludham, England."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QMIS001> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marine Isotope Stage 1 (Late Pleistocene - Holocene) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS British Regional Geology: Northern England (Fifth edition), fig. 64)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QMIS002> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marine Isotope Stage 2 (Late Pleistocene) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS British Regional Geology: Northern England (Fifth edition), fig. 64)."@en .
