+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QMIS095> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marine Isotope Stage 95 (Early Pleistocene) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QMIS096> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marine Isotope Stage 96 (Early Pleistocene) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QMIS097> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marine Isotope Stage 97 (Early Pleistocene) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QMIS098> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marine Isotope Stage 98 (Early Pleistocene) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QMIS099> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marine Isotope Stage 99 (Early Pleistocene) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QMIS100> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marine Isotope Stage 100 (Early Pleistocene) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QMIS101> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marine Isotope Stage 101 (Early Pleistocene) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QMIS102> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marine Isotope Stage 102 (Early Pleistocene) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QMIS103> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marine Isotope Stage 103 (Early Pleistocene) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QMIS104> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Marine Isotope Stage 104 (Late Pliocene) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QN> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Antian/Bramertonian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval. It is preceded by the Thurnian Stage and succeeded by the Pre-Pastonian/Baventian Stage. It is contemporaneous with Tiglian Substage C1-4b of NW Europe (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Wolstonian Stage is a Mid Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval. It is preceded by the Hoxnian Stage and succeeded by the Ipswichian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Saalian Stage of NW Europe, and with marine isotope stages 6-10 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b). It is named for the village of Wolston, Warwickshire, England."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QP> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Pleistocene Epoch is the first of the two epochs of the Quaternary Period. It is preceded by the Pliocene Epoch (Neogene Period) and succeeded by the Holocene Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 30.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QPE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Pleistocene is the first of three informal subdivisions of the Pleistocene Epoch. It equates to the Gelasian plus Calabrian ages of the international standard stratigraphic scheme (BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QPL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Pleistocene is the last of three informal subdivisions of the Pleistocene Epoch. It equates to the Upper Pleistocene Age of the international standard stratigraphic scheme (BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QPM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mid Pleistocene is the second of three informal subdivisions of the Pleistocene Epoch. It equates to the Chibanian Age of the international standard stratigraphic scheme (BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Pre-Ludhamian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is succeeded by the Ludhamian Stage. It is contemporaneous with Marine Isotope Stage 96 and greater (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Pastonian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval. It is preceded by the Pre-Pastonian/Baventian Stage and succeeded by the Beestonian Stage. It is contemporaneous with Tiglian Substage C5-6 of NW Europe (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b). It is named for the village of Paston, Norfolk, England."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QT> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Thurnian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval. It is preceded by the Ludhamian Stage and succeeded by the Antian/Bramertonian Stage. It is contemporaneous with Tiglian Substage B of NW Europe (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QV> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Pre-Pastonian/Baventian Stage is an Early Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a cold (glacial) interval. It is preceded by the Antian/Bramertonian Stage and succeeded by the Pastonian Stage. It is contemporaneous with Tiglian Substage C4c of NW Europe (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b). Replaces: Baventian Stage."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/QX> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Hoxnian Stage is a Mid Pleistocene stage in the British Quaternary climatostratigraphic scheme. It is interpreted as a temporate (interglacial) interval. It is preceded by the Anglian Stage and succeeded by the Wolstonian Stage. It is contemporaneous with the Holsteinian Stage of NW Europe, and with Marine Isotope Stage 11 (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 30.2; BGS Research Report RR/10/003, table 1b). It is named for the village of Hoxne, Suffolk, England."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/RE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Paleozoic is the first of two informal subdivisions of the Paleozoic Era. It includes the Cambrian, Ordovician and Silurian periods of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/RL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Paleozoic is the second of two informal subdivisions of the Paleozoic Era. It includes the Devonian, Carboniferous and Permian periods of the international standard stratigraphic scheme."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/RZ> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Paleozoic Era is the first of the three eras of the Phanerozoic Eon. It includes the Cambrian, Ordovician, Silurian, Devonian, Carboniferous and Permian periods. It is preceded by the Neoproterozoic Era (Proterozoic Eon) and succeeded by the Mesozoic Era (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/S> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Silurian Period is the third of the six periods of the Paleozoic Era. It is preceded by the Ordovician Period and succeeded by the Devonian Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 21.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/SA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Aeronian Age is a division of geological time within the Silurian Period. It is the second of the three ages within the Llandovery Epoch. It is preceded by the Rhuddanian Age and succeeded by the Telychian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 21.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/SD> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Ludfordian Age is a division of geological time within the Silurian Period. It is the second of the two ages within the Ludlow Epoch. It is preceded by the Gorstian Age and succeeded by the Pridoli Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 21.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/SG> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Gorstian Age is a division of geological time within the Silurian Period. It is the first of the two ages within the Ludlow Epoch. It is preceded by the Homerian Age (Wenlock Epoch) and succeeded by the Ludfordian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 21.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/SH> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Homerian Age is a division of geological time within the Silurian Period. It is the second of the two ages within the Wenlock Epoch. It is preceded by the Sheinwoodian Age and succeeded by the Gorstian Age (Ludlow Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 21.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/SL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Llandovery Epoch is the first of the four epochs of the Silurian Period. It is preceded by the Late Ordovician Epoch (Ordovician Period) and succeeded by the Wenlock Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 21.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/SO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Pridoli Epoch is the last of the four epochs of the Silurian Period. It is preceded by the Ludlow Epoch and succeeded by the Early Devonian Epoch (Devonian Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 21.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/SR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Rhuddanian Age is a division of geological time within the Silurian Period. It is the first of the three ages within the Llandovery Epoch. It is preceded by the Hirnantian Age (Ordovician Period) and succeeded by the Aeronian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 21.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/SS> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Sheinwoodian Age is a division of geological time within the Silurian Period. It is the first of the two ages within the Wenlock Epoch. It is preceded by the Telychian Age (Llandovery Epoch) and succeeded by the Homerian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 21.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/ST> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Telychian Age is a division of geological time within the Silurian Period. It is the last of the three ages within the Llandovery Epoch. It is preceded by the Aeronian Age and succeeded by the Sheinwoodian Age (Wenlock Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 21.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/SU> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Ludlow Epoch is the third of the four epochs of the Silurian Period. It is preceded by the Wenlock Epoch and succeeded by the Pridoli Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 21.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/SW> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Wenlock Epoch is the second of the four epochs of the Silurian Period. It is preceded by the Llandovery Epoch and succeeded by the Ludlow Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 21.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/T> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Triassic Period is the first of the three periods of the Mesozoic Era. It is preceded by the Permian Period (Palaeozoic Era) and succeeded by the Jurassic Period (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 2.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/TA> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Anisian Age is a division of geological time within the Triassic Period. It is the first of the two ages within the Mid Triassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Olenekian Age (Early Triassic Epoch) and succeeded by the Ladinian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 25.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/TC> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Carnian Age is a division of geological time within the Triassic Period. It is the first of the three ages within the Late Triassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Ladinian Age (Mid Triassic Epoch) and succeeded by the Norian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 25.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/TD> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Ladinian Age is a division of geological time within the Triassic Period. It is the second of the two ages within the Mid Triassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Anisian Age and succeeded by the Carnian Age (Late Triassic Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 25.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/TE> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Early Triassic Epoch is the first of the three epochs of the Triassic Period. It is preceded by the Lopingian Epoch (Permian Period) and succeeded by the Mid Triassic Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 25.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/). Replaces: Scythian Age."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/TI> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Induan Age is a division of geological time within the Triassic Period. It is the first of the two ages within the Early Triassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Changhsingian Age (Permian Period) and succeeded by the Olenekian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 25.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/TL> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Scythian Age is a deprecated term, replaced by Early Triassic Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, fig. 1.5)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/TM> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Mid Triassic Epoch is the second of the three epochs of the Triassic Period. It is preceded by the Early Triassic Epoch and succeeded by the Late Triassic Epoch (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 25.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/TN> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Norian Age is a division of geological time within the Triassic Period. It is the second of the three ages within the Late Triassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Carnian Age and succeeded by the Rhaetian Age (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 25.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/TO> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Olenekian Age is a division of geological time within the Triassic Period. It is the second of the two ages within the Early Triassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Induan Age and succeeded by the Anisian Age (Mid Triassic Epoch) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 25.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/TR> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Rhaetian Age is a division of geological time within the Triassic Period. It is the last of the three ages within the Late Triassic Epoch. It is preceded by the Norian Age and succeeded by the Hettangian Age (Jurassic Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 25.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
+<http://data.bgs.ac.uk/id/Geochronology/Division/TU> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Late Triassic Epoch is the last of the three epochs of the Triassic Period. It is preceded by the Mid Triassic Epoch and succeeded by the Early Jurassic Epoch (Jurassic Period) (Geologic Time Scale 2020, figs. 2.1, 25.1; https://timescalefoundation.org/)."@en .
